      <field name="heading_text">Giles Corey [September 19, 1692]</field>
      <field name="fulltext">Giles Corey was a Wizzard strong, A stubborn wretch was he; And fitt was he to hang on high Upon the Locust-tree.</field>
      <field name="fulltext">So when before the magistrates For triall he did come, He would no true confession make, But was compleatlie dumbe.</field>
      <field name="fulltext">“Giles Corey,” said the Magistrate, “What hast thou heare to pleade To these that now accuse thy soule Of crimes and horrid deed?”</field>
      <field name="fulltext">Giles Corey, he said not a worde, No single worde spoke he. “Giles Corey,” saith the Magistrate, “We‘ll press it out of thee.”</field>
      <field name="fulltext">They got them then a heavy beam, They laid it on his breast; They loaded it with heavy stones, And hard upon him prest.</field>
      <field name="fulltext">“More weight!” now said this wretched man; “More weight!”again he cried; And he did no confession make, But wickedly he dyed.</field>
